AGI - Sergio Mattarella landed in Dublin for a visit that will be divided between an informal meeting with President Michael D. Higgins and the donation ceremony of the garden of the residence of the Italian ambassador to the city. Higgins and Mattarella have a long and consolidated relationship, cultivated both with formal meetings and with mutual informal visits in the many years of the mandates (the Irish president has been in office since 2011), and the meeting ground has always been Europe, even in the common leadership of Arraiolos, more times enlivened by the Eurosceptic line of the presidents of the North and Visegrad countries. After some meetings in the morning, the head of the state, accompanied by his daughter Laura, will be guest of the Irish president and his wife Sabrina at the dinner offered in his honor in the presidential residence.
&nbsp;
Tomorrow morning, after some informal visits, the two presidents will be at the Lucan house, greeted by Italian ambassador Ruggero Corrias, for the inauguration ceremony of Parco Italia, a garden that so far decorated the residence of the ambassador of Rome in Ireland and which will be donated to the South Dublin County Council. Lucan House, a Palladian-style residence of the late 1700s, was the residence of the Italian Ambassadors in Ireland for over eighty years until the Italian Government decided to give it to the County of South Dublin to move to the city centre. On the initiative of the Italian ambassador and the National Gallery of Modern and Contemporary Art of Rome, the park now houses the permanent exhibition "Grazing in Lucan" composed of eight bronze buffalo and a fiberglass horse by the Italian artist Davide Rivalta. As a result of this cultural initiative and in memory of the Italian presence in this property, the area of the estate where the sculptures are placed has been called, in fact, Parco Italia.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
At the end of the ceremony Mattarella and Higgins will have an interview, then in the afternoon the president will leave for Rome. The initiative aims to seal the excellent relations between the two countries, always in deep harmony on a Europeanist line, further confirmed after Brexit. A tune that seems not to be tested even after the sudden change of leadership in the Irish government. Two months ago, on March 20, Leo Varadkar, long premier, resigned to surprise for "personal and political" reasons still unexplained but that many put in close connection with the outcome of the popular referendum on the modernization of the Constitution.
&nbsp;
On 7 March, the bipartisan referendum was rejected, also promoted with the favor of the premier, who was declared gay and led in the Liberal Conservative Party, in which the voters called to change the Charter of 1937 in the direction of greater openness to gender equality. To succeed him the young Simon Harris, for some years his minister and as exponent of the Fine Gael, who is now on the eve of the European elections leading a country that still suffers the political effects of Brexit and is shaken by demonstrations against migrants. The next political elections are scheduled for the spring of 2025 and the last polls clearly lead the Sinn Fèin, the nationalist formation of the left.&nbsp;

